# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: autonomous-university-of-madrid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The explosions killed 193 people and injured around 2,500.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The bombings constituted the deadliest terrorist attack carried out in the history of Spain and the deadliest in Europe since the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 in Scotland.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The attacks were carried out by radical Islamists who opposed Spanish indirect involvement in the 2003 US-led invasion of Iraq.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Controversy regarding the handling and representation of the bombings by the government arose, with Spain's two main political parties — the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE) and the Partido Popular (PP) — accusing each other of concealing or distorting evidence for electoral reasons.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The bombings occurred three days before general elections in which incumbent Prime Minister José María Aznar's PP was defeated.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The scale and precise planning of the attacks reared memories of the September 11 attacks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Results published in *The Review of Economics and Statistics* by economist José García Montalvo seem to suggest that indeed the bombings had important electoral impact (turning the electoral outcome against the incumbent People's Party and handing government over to the Socialist Party, PSOE).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] After 21 months of investigation, judge Juan del Olmo tried Moroccan national Jamal Zougam, among several others, for his participation carrying out the attack.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Although claims were made that attacks were linked to al-Qaeda, investigations and probes conducted by Spanish officials did not find any links to al-Qaeda.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Findings issued by the Spanish judiciary in September 2007 found 21 individuals guilty of participating in the attacks, while rejecting the involvement of an external mastermind or direct al-Qaeda links.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] During the peak of Madrid rush hour on the morning of Thursday, 11 March 2004, ten explosions occurred aboard four commuter trains (*cercanías*).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The date, 11 March, led to the abbreviation of the incident as "11-M".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] All the affected trains were traveling on the same line and in the same direction between Alcalá de Henares and the Atocha station in Madrid.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was later reported that thirteen improvised explosive devices (IEDs) had been placed on the trains.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Bomb disposal teams (TEDAX) arriving at the scenes of the explosions detonated two of the remaining three IEDs in controlled explosions, but the third was not found until later in the evening, having been stored inadvertently with luggage taken from one of the trains.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The following timeline of events comes from the judicial investigation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] All four trains had departed the Alcalá de Henares station between 07:01 and 07:14.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] At 08:00, emergency relief workers began arriving at the scenes of the bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The police reported numerous victims and mentioned 50 wounded and several dead.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] By 08:30 the emergency ambulance service, SAMUR (Servicio de Asistencia Municipal de Urgencia y Rescate), had set up a field hospital at the Daoiz y Velarde sports facility.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Bystanders and local residents helped relief workers, as hospitals were told to expect the arrival of many casualties.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] At 08:43, firefighters reported 15 dead at El Pozo.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] By 09:00, the police had confirmed the death of at least 30 people – 20 at El Pozo and about 10 in Santa Eugenia and Atocha.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] People combed the city's major hospitals in search of family members who they thought were aboard the trains.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] There were 193 confirmed dead victims, the last victim dying in 2014 after having been in a coma for 10 years due to one of the Atocha explosions and not having been able to recover from their injuries.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The total number of victims was higher than in any other terrorist attack in Spain, far surpassing the 21 killed and 40 wounded from a 1987 bombing at a Hipercor chain supermarket in Barcelona.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On that occasion, responsibility was claimed by ETA.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was Europe's worst terror attack since the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland on 21 December 1988.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] A device composed of 12 kilograms of Goma-2 ECO with a detonator and 136 meters of wire (connected to nothing) was found on the track of a high-speed railway line (AVE) on 2 April.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Spanish judiciary chose not to investigate that incident and the perpetrators remain unknown.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The device used in the AVE incident was unable to explode because it lacked an initiation system.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Shortly after the AVE incident, police identified an apartment in Leganés, south of Madrid, as the base of operations for the individuals suspected of being the perpetrators of the Madrid and AVE attacks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The suspected militants, Sarhane Abdelmaji "the Tunisian" and Jamal Ahmidan "the Chinese", were trapped inside the apartment by a police raid on the evening of 3 April.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] At 9:03 pm, when the police attempted to breach the premises, the militants committed suicide by setting off explosives, killing themselves and one of the police officers.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Investigators subsequently found that the explosives used in the Leganés explosion were of the same type as those used in the 11 March attacks (though it had not been possible to identify a brand of dynamite from samples taken from the trains) and in the thwarted bombing of the AVE line.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Based on the assumption that the militants killed at Leganés were indeed the individuals responsible for the train bombings, the ensuing investigation focused on how they obtained their estimated 200 kg of explosives.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The investigation revealed that they had been bought from a retired miner who still had access to blasting equipment.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Five to eight suspects believed to be involved in the 11 March attacks managed to escape.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In France, the Vigipirate plan was upgraded to orange level.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In Italy, the government declared a state of high alert.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In December 2004, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero claimed that the PP government erased all of the computer files related to the Madrid bombings, leaving only the documents on paper.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 25 March 2005, prosecutor Olga Sánchez asserted that the bombings happened 911 days (exactly 2 and a half years) after the 11 September attacks due to the "highly symbolic and qabbalistic charge for local Al-Qaida groups" of choosing that day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 27 May 2005, the Prüm Convention, implementing among other things the principle of availability which began to be discussed after the Madrid bombings, was signed by Germany, Spain, France, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Austria, and Belgium.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 4 January 2007, *El País* reported that Algerian Ouhnane Daoud, who is considered to be the mastermind of the 11-M bombings, has been searching for ways to return to Spain to prepare further attacks, though this has not been confirmed.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 17 March 2008, Basel Ghalyoun, Mohamed Almallah Dabas, Abdelillah El-Fadual El-Akil and Raúl González Peña, having been found guilty by the Audiencia Nacional, were released after a Higher Court ruling.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] This court also verified the release of the Egyptian Rabei Osman al-Sayed.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 14 March 2004, Abu Dujana al-Afghani, a purported spokesman for al-Qaeda in Europe, appeared in a videotape claiming responsibility for the attacks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Spanish judiciary stated that a loose group of Moroccan, Syrian, and Algerian Muslims and two Guardia Civil and Spanish police informants were suspected of having carried out the attacks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 11 April 2006, Judge Juan del Olmo charged 29 suspects for their involvement in the train bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] No evidence has been found of al-Qaeda involvement, although an al-Qaeda claim was made the day of the attacks by the Abu Hafs al-Masri Brigades.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] U.S. officials note that this group is "notoriously unreliable".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In August 2007, al-Qaeda claimed to be "proud" about the Madrid 2004 bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Mohamed Darif, a professor of political science at Hassan II University in Mohammedia, stated in 2004 that the history of the Moroccan Combat Group is directly tied to the rise of al-Qaeda in Afghanistan.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Scholar Rogelio Alonso said in 2007, "the investigation had uncovered a link between the Madrid suspects and the wider world of al-Qaida".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Scott Atran said "There isn't the slightest bit of evidence of any relationship with al-Qaida.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] We've been looking at it closely for years and we've been briefed by everybody under the sun... and nothing connects them." He provides a detailed timeline that lends credence to this view.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to the European Strategic Intelligence and Security Center, the Islamic extremists' alliance with ETA is highly dubious and "there is not anyway any terror case whatsoever to this day in which islamist internationalists collaborated with non-muslims".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Former Spanish Prime Minister José María Aznar said in 2011 that Abdelhakim Belhadj, leader of the Libyan Islamic Fighting Group and current head of the Tripoli Military Council, was suspected of complicity in the bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Immediate reactions to the attacks in Madrid were the several press conferences held by the Spanish prime minister José María Aznar involving ETA.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Spanish government maintained this theory for two days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Because the bombs were detonated three days before the general elections in Spain, the situation had many political interpretations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The United States also initially believed ETA was responsible, then questioning if Islamic extremists were responsible.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Due to the government theory, statements issued shortly after the Madrid attacks, including from lehendakari Juan José Ibarretxe identified ETA as the prime suspect, but the group, which usually claims responsibility for its actions, denied any involvement.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Later evidence strongly pointed to the involvement of extremist Islamist groups, with the Moroccan Islamic Combatant Group named as a focus of investigations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Although ETA has a history of mounting bomb attacks in Madrid, the 11 March attacks exceeded any attack previously attempted by a European organisation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] This led some experts to point out that the tactics used were more typical of militant Islamic extremist groups, perhaps with a certain link to al-Qaeda, or maybe to a new generation of ETA activists using al-Qaeda as a role model.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Observers also noted that ETA customarily, but not always, issues warnings before its mass bombings and that there had been no warning for this attack.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Europol director Jürgen Storbeck commented that the bombings "could have been ETA...
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] But we're dealing with an attack that doesn't correspond to the modus operandi they have adopted up to now".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Political analysts believe ETA's guilt would have strengthened the PP's chances of being re-elected, as this would have been regarded as the death throes of a terrorist organisation reduced to desperate measures by the strong anti-terrorist policy of the Aznar government.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On the other hand, an Islamic extremist attack would have been perceived as the direct result of Spain's involvement in Iraq, an unpopular war that had not been approved by the Spanish Parliament.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] All of the devices are thought to have been hidden inside backpacks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The police investigated reports of three people in ski masks getting on and off the trains several times at Alcalá de Henares between 7:00 and 7:10.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] A Renault Kangoo van was found parked outside the station at Alcalá de Henares containing detonators, audio tapes with Qur'anic verses, and cell phones.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The provincial chief of TEDAX (the bomb disposal experts of the Spanish police) declared on 12 July 2004 that damage in the trains could not be caused by dynamite, but by some type of military explosive, like C3 or C4.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] An unnamed source from the Aznar administration claimed that the explosive used in the attacks had been Titadine (used by ETA, and intercepted on its way to Madrid 11 days before).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In March 2007, the TEDAX chief claimed that they knew that the unexploded explosive found in the Kangoo van was Goma-2 ECO the very day of the bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] He also asserted that "it is impossible to know" the components of the explosives that went off in the trains – though he later asserted that it was dynamite.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Judge Javier Gómez Bermúdez replied "I cannot understand" to these assertions.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] A radio report mentioned a plastic explosive called "Special C".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] However, the government said that the explosive found in an unexploded device, discovered among bags thought to be victims' lost luggage, was the Spanish made Goma-2 ECO.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The unexploded device contained 10 kg (22 lb) of explosive with 1 kg (2.2 lb) of nails and screws packed around it as shrapnel.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In the aftermath of the attacks, however, the chief coroner alleged that no shrapnel was found in any of the victims.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Goma-2 ECO was never before used by al-Qaeda, but the explosive and the modus operandi were described by *The Independent* as ETA trademarks, although the *Daily Telegraph* came to the opposite conclusion.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Two bombs, one in Atocha and another in El Pozo station, numbers 11 and 12, were detonated accidentally by the TEDAX.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to the provincial chief of the TEDAX, deactivated rucksacks contained some other type of explosive.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The 13th bomb, which was transferred to a police station, contained dynamite, although it did not explode because it was missing two wires connecting the explosives to the detonator.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] That bomb used a mobile phone (Mitsubishi Trium) as a timer, requiring a SIM card to activate the alarm and thereby detonate.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The analysis of the SIM card allowed the police to arrest an alleged perpetrator.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 13 March, when three Moroccans and two Pakistani Muslims were arrested for the attacks, it was confirmed that the attacks came from an Islamist group.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Only one of the five persons (the Moroccan Jamal Zougam) detained that day was finally prosecuted.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Guardia Civil developed an extensive action plan to monitor records corresponding with the use of weapons and explosives.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] There were 166,000 inspections conducted throughout the country between March 2004 and November 2004.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] About 2,500 violations were discovered and over 3 tons of explosives, 11 kilometers of detonating cord, and over 15,000 detonators were seized.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 3 April 2004, in Leganés, south Madrid, four terrorists died in an apparent suicide explosion, killing one Grupo Especial de Operaciones (GEO) (Spanish special police assault unit) police officer and wounding eleven policemen.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to witnesses and media, between five and eight suspects escaped that day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Security forces carried out a controlled explosion of a suspicious package found near the Atocha station and subsequently deactivated the two undetonated devices on the Téllez train.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] A third unexploded device was later brought from the station at El Pozo to a police station in Vallecas, and became a central piece of evidence for the investigation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It appears that the El Pozo bomb failed to detonate because a cell-phone alarm used to trigger the bomb was set 12 hours late.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Sectors of the People's Party (PP), and certain media, such as *El Mundo* newspaper and the COPE radio station, continue to support theories relating the attack to a vast conspiracy to remove the governing party from power.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Support for the conspiracy was also given by the Asociación de Víctimas del Terrorismo (AVT), Spain's largest association of victims of terrorism.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] These theories speculate that ETA and members of the security forces and national and foreign (Moroccan) secret services were involved in the bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Madrid judge Coro Cillán continued to hear conspiracy theory cases, including one accusing government officials of ordering the scrapping of the bombed train cars in order to destroy evidence.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The public seemed convinced that the Madrid Bombings were a result of the Aznar government's alignment with the U.S. and its invasion of Iraq.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Before the attack, the incumbent Popular Party led the polls by 5 percent.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It is believed that the Popular Party would have won the election if it had not been for the terrorist attack.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Socialist Party, led by José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero, ended up winning the election by 5%.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Socialist Party had called for the removal of Spanish troops from Iraq during its campaigning.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Rodríguez Zapatero promised to remove Spanish troops by 30 June 2004, and the troops were withdrawn a month earlier than expected.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Twenty-eight percent of voters said that the bombings influenced their opinions and vote.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] An estimated 1 million voters switched their vote to the Socialist Party after the Madrid bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] These voters who switched their votes were no longer willing to support the Popular Party's stance on war policy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The bombings also influenced 1,700,000 citizens to vote who did not plan on originally voting.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On the other hand, the terrorist attacks discouraged 300,000 people from voting.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Overall, there was a net 4 percent increase in voter turnout.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Judge Juan del Olmo found "local cells of Islamic extremists inspired through the Internet" guilty for the 11 March attacks, rather than the Armed Islamic Group or the Moroccan Islamic Combatant Group.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] These local cells consisted of hashish traffickers of Moroccan origin, remotely linked to an al-Qaeda cell that had been already captured.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] These groups bought the explosives (dynamite Goma-2 ECO) from low-level thieves, police and Guardia Civil informers in Asturias using money from the small-scale drug trafficking.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to *El Mundo*, "the notes found on the Moroccan informer 'Cartagena' prove that the Police had the leaders of the cell responsible for the 11 March attacks under surveillance." However, none of the notes refer to the preparation of any terrorist attack.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The trial of 29 defendants began on 15 February 2007.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to *El País*, "the Court dismantled one by one all conspiracy theories" and demonstrated that any link with or involvement in the bombings by ETA was either misleading or groundless.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] During the trial the defendants retracted their previous statements and denied any involvement.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] According to *El Mundo* the questions of "by whom, why, when and where the Madrid train attacks were planned" are still "unanswered", because the alleged masterminds of the attacks were acquitted.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] *El Mundo* also claimed — among other misgivings — that the Spanish judiciary reached "scientifically unsound" conclusions about the kind of explosives used in the trains, and that no direct al-Qaeda link was found, thus "debunking the key argument of the official version".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Anthropologist Scott Atran described the Madrid trial as "a complete farce" stating that "There isn't the slightest bit of evidence of any operational relationship with al-Qaida".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Though the trial proceeded smoothly in its opening months, 14 of the 29 defendants began a hunger strike in May, protesting against the allegedly "unfair" role of political parties and media in the legal proceedings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Judge Javier Gómez Bermúdez refused to suspend the trial despite the strike, and the hunger strikers ended their fast on 21 May.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The last hearing of the trial was held on 2 July 2007.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 31 October 2007, the Audiencia Nacional of Spain handed down its judgements.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Of the 28 defendants in the trial, 21 were found guilty on a range of charges from forgery to murder.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Two of the defendants were each sentenced to more than 40,000 years in prison.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] On 31 October 2007, he was convicted of 191 charges of murder and 1,856 charges of attempted murder, and received a sentence of 42,922 years in confinement.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] A Spaniard, Emilio Suárez Trashorras, who supplied dynamite, stolen from a mine in Asturias in return for drugs – was sentenced to 34,715 years.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Neither is expected to serve more than 40 years, which in 2007 was the maximum prison term under by Spanish law.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In the investigations carried out to find out what went wrong in the security services, many individual instances of negligence and miscoordination between different branches of the police were found.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The group dealing with Islamist extremists was very small and in spite of having carried out some surveillances, they were unable to stop the bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Also, some of the criminals involved in the "Little Mafia" who provided the explosives were police informants and had leaked to their case officers some tips that were not followed up on.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Some of the alleged perpetrators of the bombing were reportedly under surveillance by the Spanish police since 2001.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] At the time of the Madrid bombings, Spain was well equipped with internal security structures that were, for the most part, effective in the fight against terrorism.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It became evident that there were coordination issues between police forces as well as within each of them.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The Interior Ministry focused on correcting these weaknesses.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was Spain's goal to strengthen its police intelligence in order to deal with the risks and threats of international terrorism.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] This decision for the National Police and the Guardia Civil to strengthen their counter-terrorism services, led to an increase in jobs aimed at preventing and fighting global terrorism.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Counter-terrorism services increased its employment by nearly 35% during the legislature.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Human resources in external information services, dealing with international terrorism, grew by 72% in the National Police force and 22% in the Guardia Civil.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] This is a list of suspects and convictions related to the bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The authorship of the bombings remains a controversial issue in Spain.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Sectors of the Partido Popular (PP) and some of the PP-friendly media outlets (primarily *El Mundo* and the Libertad Digital radio station) claim that there are inconsistencies and contradictions in the Spanish judicial investigation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] As Spanish and international investigations continue to claim the unlikeliness of ETA's active implication, these claims have shifted from direct accusations involving the Basque separatist organisation to less specific insinuations and general scepticism.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Additionally, there is controversy over the events that took place between the bombings and the general elections held three days later.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] In the aftermath of the bombings, there were massive street demonstrations across Spain to protest against the train bombings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] Two people died in political violence about the ETA controversy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] The international reaction was also notable, as the scale of the attack became clearer.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] A memorial service for the victims of this incident was held on 25 March 2004 at the Almudena Cathedral.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/11-march-2004-madrid-train-bombings] It was attended by King Juan Carlos I, Queen Sofía, the victims' families, and representatives from numerous other countries, including British prime minister Tony Blair, French president Jacques Chirac, German chancellor Gerhard Schröder, and U.S.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Abbot Oliba is considered a key figure in the repopulation of Catalonia based on Roman and Christian culture, and political pacifism and his assemblies of Peace and Truce of God laid the groundwork for one of the first parliaments in Europe.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is one of the three Spanish universities belonging to the Centro de Estudios Universitarios CEU educational group.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It belongs to the Catholic Association of Propagandists, an institution created in 1908 by the Jesuit priest Ángel Ayala.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The main campus of the UAO CEU is the Bellesguard Campus, in the district of Sarrià-Sant Gervasi.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The origin of the current university is in the CDES Abat Oliba, an institution created by Fundación San Pablo-CEU in 1973 in Barcelona.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The center started its activities in January 1974 through an affiliation agreement with the University of Barcelona.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1995 it became known as the Center for Higher Education Abat Oliba and offered degrees in Law, Business Administration and Management, and Economy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2003, the Parliament of Catalonia recognized Abat Oliba CEU University as a new university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1992 he acquired the complex built by the modernist architect Bernardí Martorell at the behest of the benefactor Francesca Balart, to convert it into its current headquarters, which opened in 1995.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] That same year, coinciding with the refurbishment by the architect Miquel Àngel Armengou, it was renamed the Abat Oliba Higher Education Centre, incorporating university studies in Law, Business Administration and Management and the first cycle of Economics.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Eight years later, in 2003, the Abat Oliba CEU University is recognised by Law 20/2003, of 4 July 2003, of the Parliament of Catalonia.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It thus becomes one of the three Spanish universities belonging to the CEU educational group.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The spring of 2007 saw the birth of the Goliad UAO CEU Awards, prizes given annually by the advertising and communication students of the Abat Oliba CEU University.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2012 the institution started an annual conferenced titled UAO CEU International Journalism Week, lasting an entire week (Monday to Friday), and hosting presentations by professionals and scholars of Journalism.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Also in 2012, the Abat Oliba CEU University and the totality of the Catalan universities pledged to defend the Catalan linguistic immersion model and proposed a coordinated access to the Catalan university system.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The university's rectors since then have been: Juan Corona Ramón (2003–2004) José María Alsina Roca (2004–2009); Carlos Pérez del Valle (2009–2017), Eva Perea (2017-2018), Rafael Rodriguez-Ponga y Salamanca (2019-2024) and Arcadi Gual Sala (since 2024).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] They offer undergraduate, master's and postgraduate degrees in the areas of Communication, Law and Political Science, Education, Business and Economics, Humanities and Psychology.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2017 Unesco awarded the UAO CEU the Chair of Peace, Solidarity and Intercultural Dialogue, to promote a comprehensive concept of peace.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] 2020 saw the creation of the Antonio de Montserrat Chair of Global Studies and the Jean Monnet Chair on Fiscal Integration in the European Union, financed with European competitive funds from the Erasmus+ call for Jean Monnet activities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] There is also the Labour Observatory, dedicated to current issues in the world of work, and the Institute of Health Sciences.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2020, the university joined the European Federation of Catholic Universities and the International Platform for Cooperation and Migration.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is part of the CEU educational group and is one of three CEU Universities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In addition to its research and teaching function, UAO CEU organises cultural and informative activities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] 2007 saw the creation of the annual GoliADs UAO CEU Awards for advertising and communication, awarded by students of Abat Oliba CEU University in Barcelona to advertising agencies and the media.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Since 2013, it has organised the BCN Thinking Challenge, a university marathon of social entrepreneurship created by the university's Entrepreneurship Club.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2015, the Education Talks were created, spaces for innovation in education which are organised in two annual sessions, one session on educational innovation and another on a monographic theme.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2017, the Digital Communication Week was launched.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Two editions have been held: one focused on the role of artificial intelligence and the other on digital transformation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is held as part of the Official Master’s Degree in Digital Communication and New Technologies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Other conferences that the UAO CEU organises are the Law and Society Conference and the European Conference of Christian Anthropology and Mental Health Sciences, which were held for the first time in September 2018 and 2019, respectively.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The UAO CEU was the first university to join the ‘Universitats amb cor’ programme of Caritas Internationalis in Barcelona.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] It is part of the CEU educational group, the private educational institution that allocates most resources in Spain to scholarships and study grants.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the 2009 Spanish universities ranking by the Institute for Industrial and Financial Analysis (IAIF) of the Complutense University of Madrid, the Abat Oliba CEU University ranks 1st among the Catalan private universities in terms of teaching.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In research, the university holds the 3rd position nationwide.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] One of the patrons of the university is the Archbishop of Barcelona, currently Juan José Omella.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] UAO CEU is the highest-ranking private Catalan university in Spain, as accredited by the Institute of Industrial and Financial Analysis (IAIF) of the Complutense University of Madrid.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In Spain, UAO CEU ranks third place, behind only the University of Navarra and the Comillas Pontifical University.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the study Via Universitària (2016), by the Jaume Bofill Foundation and the Xarxa Vives d'Universitats 85% of UAO CEU students are satisfied with their studies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The seventh ranking of universities of the CyD Foundation (2020) highlighted the performance of UAO CEU in the fields of international mobility, international teaching staff, placements in companies in the region, graduation rate and rate of return on degree.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] According to the QS World University Rankings, drawn up by Times Higher Education, CEU universities are among the 500 best in the world and rank sixth among Spanish universities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] UAO CEU has its main campus at the Bellesguard Campus, located around the former summer palace of the House of Barcelona, where King Martin of Aragon, also known as Martin the Humane, died.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 1900, part of the plot was segregated so that the architect Antoni Gaudí could build a residence for the industrialist Jaume Figueres, known as Torre Bellesguard.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] On the rest of the land, in 1925, the Oblates of the Most Holy Redeemer promoted a religious community for carrying out social work, built by the architect Bernardí Martorell thanks to the generosity of Francesca Balart.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] Martorell, a disciple of Gaudí, designed a church with hyperboloid vaults, which today serves as the Aula Magna / Aula Sacra.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] The church and the cloister were fitted out as headquarters for the UAO CEU by the architect Miquel Àngel Armengou in 1992.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2018, refurbishment work was undertaken in the Aula Magna / Aula Sacra, with the installation of an underfloor heating system and new audiovisual equipment.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abat-oliba-ceu-university] In 2019, the new radio, television and photography studios were inaugurated.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The **Abdelmalek Essaâdi University** is a Moroccan public university established in 1989 and headquartered in Tétouan.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is one of the main higher education institutions in northern Morocco.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university comprises 15 institutions, including faculties, schools, and institutes, distributed across the Tanger-Tétouan-Al Hoceïma region as well as in the city of Larache.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It offers programs in several fields, including sciences, law, economics and management, humanities and social sciences, as well as science and technology.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In 2016, the university inaugurated a Confucius Institute dedicated to the teaching of Chinese language and culture, becoming the third institute of this type in Morocco.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university was ranked 82nd in the 2016 regional ranking of Arab universities published by U.S.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Abdelmalek Essaâdi University was founded by virtue of Dahir no.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] 177-398 of 16 October 1975 relating to the creation of universities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In addition to the Presidency, the UAE currently has 15 institutions, namely: six schools and nine faculties.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] In addition, 2 schools and 6 faculties will soon be opened..
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university includes the following faculties and schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The National Schools and the faculty of science and technology deliver a state engineering degree (Diplôme d'Ingénieur d'État).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The other faculties deliver either a bachelor's (licence) or a master's degree.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university's initial and continuing education programs are aimed at all audiences and offer accredited training in many areas.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university prepares training offers according to the Bachelor framework for accreditation and start of application from the start of the 2021–2022 academic year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The UAE has been able to develop interesting and promising research potential.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Research at UAE is now structured within 5 CEDs, 38 laboratories, 20 groups and 52 research teams accredited by the University Council (CU).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] For its part, research and international cooperation have been defined in the university's development strategy as priorities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is the guarantor of training and research with an international dimension allowing the university to welcome and train foreign students and to offer its students and staff the opportunity of a departure towards other cultures, with a very present African dimension.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The university provides students with a web platform providing resources (PDF courses, videos, etc.) for all branches of study.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The Confucius Institute inaugurated in 2016, is the 3rd Confucius Institute in Morocco with the objective of learning the Chinese language.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The result of a partnership between UAE, Jiangxi Normal University of Science and Technology (China), HANBAN and the General Directorate of Confucius Institutes.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Since its inception, 2,308 students have registered for Chinese language and culture courses, including 308 ISITT students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The Career Center was created in 2016 with the aim of offering UAE students training in "Soft-Skills" non-technical skills and facilitating their access to employability after their university studies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] More than 15,000 students have benefited from its physical services and nearly 200,000 virtual users have registered on the careercenter.ma platform, which has received more than 1,915,000 visits.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The center uses computer-aided design, engineering, manufacturing and materials science technologies to transform a 3D model into a physical object.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The objective is to develop applied research meeting the needs to support regional and national socio-economic development.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] A center created to support all components of the university and instill a spirit of tolerance, multiculturalism, law and duty.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Several associations and clubs active in sport, charity work, art, journalism, innovation and entrepreneurship are present in the various schools and institutions of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] There is also a Student Office in all components of the UAE, which oversees the protection of student rights and the transmission of information to the administrative body.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] Abdelmalek Essaâdi University has signed agreements with its international counterparts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] It is an effective partner of more than 32 universities around the world, and foresees a number of 50 in 2023.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdelmalek-essaâdi-university] The partnership with the socioeconomic fabric on a multidimensional scale is very present.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] Almuhannadi was born on August 7, 1973, in Al Khor, Qatar.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] He obtained a bachelor's degree in law from Beirut Arab University in 2000.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] He also holds a master's degree in law from the Autonomous University of Madrid, Diploma in Sports Management from Cairo University, and Diploma in Public Relations and Media Management from the University of Houston in 2015.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] Almuhannadi began his career in journalism and media in 1991, when he worked as a public relations officer at the Qatari Emiri Diwan until 1995.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] He then became Deputy Head of Public Relations from 1995 to 2009.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] From 2000 to 2004, he was the Secretary of the Qatar National Teams Committee in the Qatar Football Association.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] He was Director of Legal Affairs at the Qatar Football Association between 2005 and 2008, then Director of Legal Affairs at the Qatar Stars League from 2008 to 2010.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] In 2016, he became CEO of Al-Khor Sports Club.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] From 2019 to 2023, he was editor-in-chief of *Al Raya*, a Qatari newspaper.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/abdulla-ghanim-almuhannadi] Almuhannadi also served as Head of Local Affairs and Editor-in-Chief of Local Affairs and Economic Sectors at Al-Watan.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] An **academic year**, or **school year**, is a period that schools, colleges and universities use to measure the duration of studies for a given educational level.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Academic years are often divided into academic terms.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Students attend classes and do relevant exams and homework during this time, which comprises school days (days when there is education) and school holidays (when there is a break from education).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] The duration of school days, holidays and school year varies across the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] The days in the school year depend on the state or country.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] For example, in most of the US states, there are 180 days in a school year, but in the US state of Minnesota there are 165 days in the year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] A "school day" is a day when school is open.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Governments often legislate on the total number of school days in a year for government funded (i.e., not private) schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] School holidays (also referred to as vacations, breaks, and *recess*) are periods during which schools are closed or no classes or other mandatory activities are held.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] The dates and periods of school holidays vary considerably throughout the world, and there is usually some variation even within the same jurisdiction.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] The holidays given below apply to primary and secondary education.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Teaching sessions (terms or semesters) in tertiary education are usually longer.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In the northern hemisphere, many school districts have traditionally offered a week-long vacation in the spring, often called **Spring Vacation** or **Spring Break**.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In parochial schools and jurisdictions that follow a Christian religious tradition, the vacation may be described as an Easter holiday, which starts on Good Friday and continues through the subsequent week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In the northern hemisphere, the longest break in the educational calendar is in the middle of the year, during the northern summer, and lasting up to 14 weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In Ireland, Italy, Latvia, Lithuania, and Russia, summer holidays typically last three months, compared to six to eight weeks in Britain, the Netherlands, and Germany.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In India, summer holidays typically span a duration of one to two months, extending from May to June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In the southern hemisphere, the longest break in the educational calendar is in the end-beginning of the year, during the southern summer, and lasts up to 14 weeks, from December 21 to March 20.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Traffic congestion and heavy passenger loads on public transport on school run routes may be worse on school days during term time.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Summer holidays for most children are a time to relax, enjoy themselves, catch up on studies, or spend time with family or relatives.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] Many families travel together on school holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] School holidays have many effects on a country, ranging from the price of travel and holiday accommodation, which increase as demand increases while children are off school, to a change in crime rate.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] The number of families taking holidays away from urban areas can reduce traffic and use of public transport in cities while loading long-distance highways and means of transport.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p01] In some countries where many families travel to their holiday destinations, such as the Netherlands, the start and end dates of school holidays in different regions are staggered to reduce the heavy traffic and pressure on means of transport that would otherwise occur on these dates.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Nigeria, the longest holiday is from January ending to first or second week of November for secondary schools and a longer duration within same period for tertiary institutions.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Holidays are generally determined by schools and typically run from July to the early days of September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Egypt, the longest holiday is usually from May ending on the start of October.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] There is also a mid-term break between semesters that lasts 3–4 weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The South Africa academic calendar starts in mid-January and ends in early December.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The academic lesson for the school year ends in mid-October, with final examinations taking place from late October to late November.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The learners usually stop attending class after their last exam.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In essence, the December closing is more for teachers and school staff to mark exams and prepare end-year school reports to issue on the last day of the academic calendar.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The year is divided into four academic terms, with the first term starting in mid-January and ending in late March or early April.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The second term starts in early or mid-April and ends in late June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The third term runs from early July to late September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The fourth and last term usually starts at the beginning of October and closes in mid-December when the academic year officially comes to an end.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In South Africa, the main holiday usually lasts from early December to early or mid-January (5 or 6 weeks).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] There is an autumn break of up to two weeks in late March or early April, a longer winter break in late June and early July normally around three weeks, and a spring break in late September or early October which is one week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] South African schools and universities are closed on all South African public holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In terms of the Public Holidays Act, if the holiday falls on a Sunday, then schools are closed the following Monday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Brazilian schools must have at least 200 school days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Brazil, summer holidays start in late November or early December and end in late January or early February.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Winter holidays are generally the entire month of July, while in some states it lasts during the São João recess.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Some schools in the tropical north follow a different school year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The Brazilian Carnival is 40 days before Easter Sunday and those dates are not school holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Some national and Catholic holidays are usually celebrated in 3 or 4 days, like Easter, Corpus Christi and Carnival.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Canada, the school year typically lasts between 185 and 190 days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The summer holiday includes the months of July and August, with students returning to school in late August or early September, most commonly on the day after Labour Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The winter break lasts for two weeks (sometimes a day or two longer), beginning on Saturday and encompassing Christmas Day and New Year's Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The spring break is one to two weeks long depending on the city or province.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Good Friday and Easter may or may not fall within spring break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The Thanksgiving break is a 3-day break that falls in mid-October.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Ontario, the school year is regulated to last at least 194 days, with up to seven of those days being professional activity days, for a total minimum of 187 instructional days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Spring break (commonly known as March Break) is the third week in March.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The school year is divided into semesters.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The first semester runs from late February or early March to July.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Following a two- or three-week winter break, school resumes and lasts until early or mid-December, followed by 10–12 weeks of summer vacations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In addition, schools have a one-week-long break for National Holidays in mid-September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Being located in the Southern Hemisphere, spring begins approximately at the end of this holiday week so it acts similarly to the American spring break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] There is also a brief Easter break in March or April.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Public schools averaged 180 school days in the 2023 academic year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] However, different states have different legal minimum requirements for instructional days and hours per year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In 2023 the number of instructional days required ranged from the lowest minimum of 160 in the state of Colorado to the highest minimum of 186 in the state of Kansas.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Most states require around 180 school days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] School years at colleges/universities are often shorter, ranging from 140 to 160 days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Private schools tend to have classes for 170 days each year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] An academic year typically includes a fall and spring semester, with a shorter optional summer session.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Many also have a short optional winter session or a wheel-rotation schedule year-round.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] One theory to explain the long summer break is that when the United States was a primarily agrarian society, children were needed during the Northern Hemisphere summer months for farm labor.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] However, there is little evidence supporting this, with 19th-century rural schools more typically favoring a summer academic term and more vacation time during spring and autumn.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Summer is still a popular time for family vacations, and most have a two or three-month summer vacation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The academic year typically runs from August or early September until late May or early June, depending on the length of the year and number of the holiday, vacation, and snow days occurring during the year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The year is divided into two semesters, three trimesters or four quarters, also called marking periods, typically with a report card issued to students' parents at the end of each.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Continuing education classes (often available at community colleges and private "boot camp" style schools) are often shorter and start throughout the year with no particular seasonality.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] For college sports sanctioned by the National Collegiate Athletic Association and its associated conferences, their calendar for the year starts on July 1, with the year ending on the succeeding June 30, with other multiple calendars for each sport regarding recruiting and competition periods.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Some closely follow the K-12 break schedule, others have the same but longer breaks to accommodate students who live farther away and wish to return home for holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Most colleges and university years are divided into two semesters.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The first starting from the beginning of the year (August/September) until mid-December, and the second lasting from January until early May.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Winter and summer classes could be taken in between the breaks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Summer holidays usually last from early July to the start of September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The winter holiday usually lasts 1 month, and its time varies depending on the date of the Chinese New Year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Hong Kong summer holidays last from mid-July to the end of August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Christmas, Lunar New Year and Easter holidays last usually for one and a half weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The academic year in India normally starts from June/July till March/April for students in ***Nursery*** ***to Class 8***.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] For students who are in ***Class 9 and 11***, the year starts from June/July till February/March ending earlier than usual Academic Year so the students can be promoted to ***Class 10 and 12*** (respectively) .
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The academic year for class 10 and 12 is from March/April till February align with the 'board exam' during March through April/May.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The students who are currently in or going into *Class 10 and 12* would get a shorter 1 month summer break and one or two weeks of winter break based on the state in which they live.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The summer holidays and vacations for the rest of the classes are as follows.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In South India, summer vacations last from the end of March or early April to the end of May or beginning or middle of June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Colleges and Universities usually start in July/ August, usually after Results announcements of the Board Exam and Admission but there are private universities or colleges which usually start in June/July.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] 1 week) and at the end of December (approx.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] 1–2 weeks, aligning with Christmas/New Year holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In South India, Diwali break begins in either October or November, depending on the month Diwali occurs in that year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] It lasts for about three days to one week depending on the state/union territory.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Christmas break starts on the last week of December (22nd or 23rd) and ends on the first week of January (5th) or might last for only two days and a one-day break for the New Year again depending on the state/union territory.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The festivals Dusherra and Sankranti are also given holidays for half a month and four days respectively which can vary again based on state/union territory.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Tamil Nadu, a southern state, a one-day holiday is given for Diwali.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Tamil Nadu celebrates the Pongal festival (Thai Pongal), a 4-day festival which, according to the Tamil calendar, is usually celebrated from January 14 to January 17.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] North India: In North India, the typical summer vacation runs from mid-May to the end of June, with school usually starting on July 1.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In North India, Navaratri break is usually for 10 days, and Dussehra lies in the middle.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Christmas holidays are not usually given; however, some schools combine the Christmas holidays with the winter break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Schools in Uttar Pradesh give a holiday on Charan Singh's birthday, and that is when the winter break starts for some.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] For some other schools, the winter break starts on 28 December and usually ends on the second weekend of the new year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] There are many public holidays in India, depending on the region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Certain holidays are mandated across the nation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] States and union territories have their own dates for their state foundation days and their own list of holidays based on regions and States/ Union territories.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Besides the main holidays, there are many small holidays which take place for 1–2 days, such as Independence Day, religious breaks, and Teachers' Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Israel, the school year begins on September 1.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The last day of school is June 30 for primary school and middle school, and June 20 for high schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In universities and colleges, the academic year is divided into two semesters.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The first one begins in September or October (depending on the Hebrew calendar.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Mostly a week or two after Simchat Torah), and it ends 13 weeks after in January.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Then the next six weeks of January and February are dedicated to the first semester exams.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Afterwards, in late February or early March, begins the second semester until mid- or late June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] When the months of June and July are dedicated to the second semester exams while late testing can be by middle of August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Japan, the new academic year starts in early April.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] There are some exceptions in northern Japan, where schools set a longer winter break, while cutting the summer one shorter.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Korea, the school year starts at the beginning of March.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] From 2015 onwards, the calendar was changed to a more quasi-Western styled one, having the year to end on January rather than February.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Malaysia, there are 2 main semester holiday and an additional of mid-term break and year end holiday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The mid-year holidays last for two weeks, from late May until mid-June, in between the two school terms.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The year-end holidays last for six weeks, from mid-November until early January, in between two school years.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Each school term has a mid-term break; one week in March for the first semester and one week in the months of August or September (variable) for the second semester.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Schools are closed on national and state public holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Schools are allowed to have a few special holidays without replacement for events such as school anniversaries and sports days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] For festivities such as Hari Raya Puasa, Chinese New Year and Deepavali, schools usually apply for additional holidays to allow longer breaks for students to visit relatives in their hometowns.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] However, every day missed exceeding the special holiday allowance would be replaced by having classes on weekends.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In the Philippines, until 2020 the school calendars began in June and ended in March or early April.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] By government regulation, schools cannot start classes beyond August or earlier than June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] At the end of August around National Heroes' Day, a 3-day long weekend including the last Monday of August, was also taken.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] During the implementation of COVID-19 community quarantines in 2020 to 2022, the school year ran from September or October to May or June, in 2021, it fell in August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The summer or mid-year break begins from early June till late or middle of August and is also known as the Independence Day break as Independence Day, June 12, falls during the mid year vacation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] With the move of the calendar for most schools, an additional break, Easter break was added, corresponding to Holy Week up to Easter Sunday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Starting in 2024, a slow transition phase to the old calendar began only for public schools, with private schools having the choice to either make the transition back or to maintain the Western-styled calendar.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Public schools and those private schools who have opted to join them are expected to open in June and end in April by school year 2026–27.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In April 2026, DepEd implements a three-term school calendar in basic education, starting by SY 2026-2027.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] For universities and colleges, the four breaks in their collegiate calendar (three for trimestral institutions) closely match those of the 2021 national basic education calendar.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Since 2016–17, most of these higher learning institutions begin their year in August or September, matching the Western calendar.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Event-based holidays are declared by the President (for national holidays) and the provincial governor or city mayor for local holidays through the Department of Education (DepEd) for basic education and Commission on Higher Education (CHED) for colleges and universities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Singapore, there are four school terms.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Terms 1 and 2 are referred to as *Semester 1*, as terms 3 and 4 are referred to as *Semester 2*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Term 1 starts the day immediately after New Year's Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] If the first school day is a Thursday or a Friday, it is not counted as a school week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] After term 1, there is a break of a week, called the March Holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Thereafter, term 2 commences and is followed by a break of four weeks, the June Holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] It is followed by term 3, after which there will be another break of one week, the September Holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Then, term 4 would start, and after it there is the December holidays, which would be either five or six weeks long, depending on whether the first week of the year was counted as a school week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Students are also given days off on public holidays, as well as Children's Day, Youth Day, Teachers' Day and the day after National Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] There are Ramadan Feast (3 days) and Sacrifice Feast (4 days) holidays, but exact dates of these holidays change every year because Ramadan & Sacrifice Feasts are calculated according to Muslim calendar, resulting these feasts to be celebrated earlier by 10 or 11 days each year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] If these feasts are at the middle of the week, then the break becomes a full week break with the Arafah (the day before the feast) day also included in the break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] Other Islamic occasions are celebrated by a holiday or a short break, like the Eid break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] The academic year in Vietnam consists of two semesters, with the Tet break in between.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, academic years for primary and secondary institutions are divided into four 10-week 'terms' per year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Following southern hemisphere seasons, the main summer holiday between academic years encompasses most of December, all of January and sometimes a few days at the beginning of February, and always encompasses Christmas and New Year as well as usually Australia Day on 26 January.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In year 12, the term ends in November; for those who go on to university, the term usually starts in late February or early March.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] New Zealand celebrates Waitangi Day on 6 February; the summer holidays in New Zealand may or may not extend as far as that day, depending on the year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Australia, there is typically a break of two weeks mid-semester (i.e. after Term 1 and after Term 3) and a break of three weeks in the middle of the year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the year 2000, due to the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney, the state of New South Wales extended the break after Term 3 to three weeks, compensating by reducing the break in the middle of the year to two weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In New Zealand, there is a two-week break between each term.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Typically, the Term 1 holidays will run for two weeks within April; the mid-year holidays encompass the last week of June and the first two weeks of July; and the Term 3 holidays encompass the last week of September and the first week of October.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] This varies between jurisdictions, and exact dates depend on what day of the week these respective months begin, as (with the exception of the beginning and end of the academic year), terms tend to begin and end with full weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Austria, the summer holidays are usually between early July and early September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is, with the exception of Vorarlberg and Salzburg, no Autumn break but there is a Christmas break (from December 24 until January 6) and an Easter break (lasts for 10 days).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The mid-term break in February lasts for a week and the Whitsun break lasts for 4 days including the weekend.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There are also days off during religious holidays (Assumption, Ascension, Corpus Christi etc.).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] For Flemish speaking primary schools, the academic year in Belgium begins on the first weekday in September and ends on the last weekday in June, with the summer holiday comprising the entire months of July and August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Secondary schools and universities often close about a week earlier, as soon as school results have been processed and published.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] A week of autumn break is usually scheduled during the week of All Saints’ Day (November 1).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The winter- or Christmas holiday lasts two weeks and encompasses both Christmas and New Year's Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The dates for both the one-week spring break and the two-week Easter holiday vary.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In catholic regions where carnival is celebrated, spring break usually takes place during the carnival week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] To get al balance in school days between spring break and summer holiday, the two weeks of Easter holiday can take place with Easter both at the beginning, the middle or the end of the holiday period.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In some cases, when Easter is at the complete end of the holiday, Easter Monday serves as an additional day off.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] However, in 2008 Belgium did not have the Easter Weekend inside its break due to the fact that Easter Sunday was on 23 March and schools broke up on the first weekend in April 2008 and had the two weeks then.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Croatia, there can be anywhere from three to five major breaks throughout the school year at public schools, depending on the region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Regardless of the number of holidays a school decides to have, a school year must have a minimum of 175 working days, or 160 for students undertaking the final exam at the end of high school.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Some schools have opted to shorten the winter holidays in exchange for an **Autumn break**, which typically lasts for one week around All Saints' Day (November 1).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Other free days include public holidays and local patron saint days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] If these land on a Tuesday or Thursday, the day before (Monday, if the holiday is on Tuesday) of after (Friday, if it's on Thursday), is usually also considered a free day, to "merge" the holiday with the weekend.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the Czech Republic, the summer holidays begin at the end of the school year around 30 June and end at the start of the school year on 1 September or soon thereafter.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Then there are autumn holidays: two days plus 28 October (the date of the proclamation of Czechoslovakia).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The winter (Christmas) holidays last usually from 22 December to 3 January.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is also a one-day half term holiday on 31 January.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The spring holidays are a week long and may occur in February or March, depending on the region, sometimes they continue with Easter holidays (Maundy Thursday, Good Friday and Easter Monday).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There are also free days such as 1 May (International Workers' Day), 8 May (end of World war two) and 28 September (The assassination of St.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Wenceslas - the duke and the patron saint of the Czech lands).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The school director is authorised to add up to three more free days during the school year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The school holidays are determined by the Ministry of Schools for each school year and are valid for every basic and high school.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Denmark the summer holiday lasts 6–7 weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Most schools also have one week of winter holiday and one week of autumn holiday, usually in February and October respectively.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Estonia, summer holidays last for three months, from June to August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Winter breaks last for two weeks, while autumn and spring are each one week, respectively.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In 2017, the Estonian Ministry of Education and Research began scheduling a new "winter-spring" break, to balance the learning weeks between the winter and spring holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Thus, there are now five Estonian holidays—autumn (21-29 October), winter (23 December-7 January), the "new" holiday (24 February-4 March), spring break (21 April-1 May) and summer break (12 June-31 August).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Depending on the year, summer break may, or may not, begin one week later or earlier.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] French school holidays are scheduled each year by the Ministry of National Education.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Due to the popularity of many French locales amongst international and domestic tourists, these periods can often see overcrowding in the larger cities and resort towns, such as the South of France, the Mediterranean coast and the French Riviera, as well as in Paris, Lyon, Marseille and Nice.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The Alps, with their many ski resorts and winter activities, are especially popular around the Christmas holiday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In an attempt to alleviate this issue, France's school holiday schedules are staggered by dividing the country's breaks into three different "zones" or periods.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] However, this division still does not lighten the flow of human traffic completely, as many families head to popular holiday spots all at once or on the same day, resulting in localised inflation and price increases, as well as potential availability or vacancy issues.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Holidays are divided into three separate zones except for the first two—the All Saints' Day and Christmas–New Year's.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Germany, around 75 weekdays in the year are school-free days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The exact dates are chosen by each of the 16 states, often in consultation with each other for reasons of planning and traffic management.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The usual holiday blocks are: Christmas (about 2 weeks), Easter (about 2 weeks), Summer (6 weeks), Autumn (about 2 weeks).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Depending on the state, there may be further holidays around Pentecost or in winter between the first and the second half of the school year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Some states allow municipalities or individual schools to move a handful of days from a state-wide holiday to locally favoured dates, e.g.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Shrove Monday, the Fridays after Ascension and Corpus Christi or some other Friday or Monday that would provide a long weekend and is called a *Brückentag* ("bridging day").
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Greece, there are three breaks throughout the school year at public schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The dates for the start and the end of the school year at both primary and post-primary level are not fixed, but mid-year breaks are standardised.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Due to the start of certificate exams, post-primary schools are usually not open for tuition after the Friday before the June public holiday (the first Monday in June) in any year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Primary schools must be open for a minimum of 182 days of tuition a year and for secondary schools that number is 166.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Primary schools will generally finish by 30 June, or the last Friday of June for summer break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Italy, most school holidays are determined by the Ministry of Education, and are valid for all public schools of every order and grade.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Typically, there are **Summer holidays** from early or mid-June up to the second week of September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Locally, school authorities have freedom upon the establishment of the lessons calendar to grant further vacation days on important local festivals (e.g. the local patron saint day).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Latvia, summer holidays last for three months from June to August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Christmas holidays last for two weeks, autumn and spring holidays are each one week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the Netherlands, summer holidays last for six weeks for all Schools, but often unofficially 7 for secondary schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The country is divided into three regions which start their summer holidays one week after another.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Summer holidays usually start in mid-July and end in late August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] May holidays span a period of national holidays such as King's Day (former Queen's Day) (April 27), Remembrance of the Dead (May 4) and Liberation Day (May 5) and sometimes include Ascension Day and Pentecost.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In North Macedonia, there are two breaks throughout the school year at public schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Other free days include the public holidays and local or School patron days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Norway, school holidays vary by region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Generally, the school year starts around the third week of August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Most regions have a week off at the beginning of October (weeks 40 or 41).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Christmas holidays start some days before Christmas Eve and end in the first week of January.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is one week of winter vacation in late February (weeks 8 or 9).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Easter holiday is from Palm Sunday to Easter Monday or a day or two later, and Summer holidays begin some days before midsummer.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] All schools have basically the same period of a school year, it starts around mid September until mid/end of June (with some exceptions).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Higher Education (Universities, Polytechnic Institutes, University Institutes, etc.) it can go from beginning of September to mid/end of July.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Portugal, the majority of schools organize their school year in 3 terms, in Higher Education are organized in 2 semesters.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Usually there are other small holidays around Carnival (in February), around 2 or 3 days, but not every school does it.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Students from years that have Final Exams (9th grade, 11th and 12th grade), usually end their classes some days/weeks before the others.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Summer breaks run from late May-mid-June to early-mid-September and are around 13–15 weeks long.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Pupils/students in the 8th and 12th grades usually enter summer break a week or two earlier than everyone else from other grades.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Spring breaks are usually one to two weeks long, between late March and early May depending on the dates of both Orthodox and Catholic Easter.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There can be two spring breaks if the Catholic and Orthodox Easter dates are very different.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Winter break is three weeks long (it usually starts in the third or fourth week of December and it ends on the second or third Monday of January).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is also a one-week long fall break, which is usually between late October and early November; however, it was limited to pupils in preschool and primary education; everyone else had a full learning period between the summer and winter breaks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Starting from 2022, though, the fall break has been applied to middle and high schools, too.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] From the 2019–2020 school year onwards (with the exception of the 2020–2021 school year), the start of the winter break marks the end of the first semester, with the beginning of the second semester immediately after the winter break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] From 2022 to 2023, there is a break in February (however, this is not between semesters), and the counties can decide each which week of February.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Slovakia, summer holidays begin at the end of the school year on June 30 and end at the start of the school year in early September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The autumn holidays are at the end of October.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The winter (Christmas) holidays usually last from December 23 to January 7.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The spring holidays are a week long and may be in February or March, depending on the region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Next are the Easter holidays (Maundy Thursday, Good Friday, Easter Monday and Easter Tuesday).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There are also free days such as May 1, May 8, and September 15.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The school director is authorized to add up to three more free days during the school year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The school holidays are determined by the Ministry of Schools and are valid for every basic and high school.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Slovenia, summer holidays begin on June 24 (June 25 is National day, which is also a public holiday) and end on September 1.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Other holidays are usually one week long, they expand if national holidays fall on the work days.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The autumn holidays ("Krompirjeve počitnice" – "Potato holidays") begin around October 31, which is Reformation day and November 1 which is called "All Saints' Day".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The New Year holidays usually start around Christmas and last until January 2.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the middle of February there are winter holidays, which are divided into two parts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In each part there are other Slovenian students who have holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The second part of the winter holiday usually ends at the end of February.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The shortest holidays are First May holidays, and as their name suggests they begin on around May 1 (usually on April 27, which is Uprising Against the Occupation Day, which is also a national holiday) and last until May 2, which is also a national holiday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There are also free days such as February 8 (Slovenian cultural festival – Prešeren Day) and Easter Monday, and other national holidays like August 15 (Feast of the Assumption) fall on school holidays and are more important to adults.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Students from the last year of primary and secondary schools usually start summer holidays one week earlier due to the final exams.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] These holidays are valid for primary and secondary schools only and are determined by the Ministry of Schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] University students, however, have summer holidays until October 1; however, the exams from spring examination period can be after 25 June and the summer examination period starts in September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Usually students have only one other holiday and that is the New Year holiday but it depends on every single college which days will be free for students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] For example, in 2015, most university students also had First May holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Short holidays usually begin after exams and depend on how good students are at their exams or how many exams they have taken for each term.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Most of the time, university students have holidays on national holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Sweden, the school year starts around mid- or late August (early September at the universities).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The week before All Saint's Day (taken as a Saturday around November 2) primary and secondary school students have an autumn holiday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Christmas holiday starts around December 19–20, depending on the day of the week on which Christmas Eve occurs.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] It usually ends some days after January 6, which is also a public holiday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In March, primary and secondary school students have one week of winter vacation; the exact week varies by location.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Easter public holidays last four days from Friday to Monday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Easter school holidays are either the week preceding Easter or the week immediately following, depending on location.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In late May, students in primary and secondary schools always receive two days off during Ascension Day and the Friday following Ascension Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Primary and secondary school summer holidays last about ten weeks, usually starting in the second week of June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] School holidays in the United Kingdom follow a standard pattern, with a school year of 190 days of teaching, beginning with the Autumn Term, but the exact timing varies between countries and counties.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Private schools may follow different terms, and some self-governing academies follow different termly structures.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In England and Wales, local authorities set term dates which apply to all Community, Voluntary Controlled, Community Special Schools and Maintained Nursery Schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Academies, Free schools, Voluntary Aided schools and Foundation schools are able to choose their own dates, but many follow the same dates as the Local Authority.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Although these schools can set their own term dates, they are still required to open for the same length of time.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Independent private schools tend to set longer holidays than state schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The academic year usually runs from the first week of September of one year through to the third week of July of the following year, with the time split up into three terms.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Each of these is usually divided into halves with a week-long "half-term" break between.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Primary (4–11) and secondary (11–16) schools usually follow a 39-week academic year, while further (16+) and higher (18+) educational establishments often have 33 or even 36-week terms, generally with no half-term break.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Oxford and Cambridge universities have shorter terms still, usually eight weeks each term.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] At English state schools, the year commences the first week of September, with a half-term break (one week) at the end of October, and the first term ending the third week of December.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] After a two-week holiday, encompassing Christmas and New Year, the second term runs from early January to Easter and is of variable length to allow for the movable feast.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is a half-term break around mid-February and two weeks of the Easter holidays, before the third and final term starts, lasting until the third week of July.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The half-term break is at the end of May and students with exams will often finish their studies at that break and take exams during June and July.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Summer holidays in State schools are usually between five and seven weeks long, starting in mid-late July and ending in early September.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Schools have Christmas and Easter holidays, each usually lasting about two weeks.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The school year is split up into three sections: Autumn term (between Summer and Christmas); Spring term (between Christmas and Easter); and Summer term (between Easter and the Summer holiday).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Roughly half-way through each term, pupils will get one week off school, known as half-term.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the Autumn term, half-term often falls the week of Halloween and close to Bonfire Night.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the Spring term, half-term tends to fall the week of Valentine's Day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In the Summer term, half-term tends to be at the end of May with students returning the first Monday of June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Independent schools often have longer holidays including up to 10 weeks for Summer, but often have longer school days and sometimes lessons on Saturday mornings.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] See English school holidays for the impact of school holidays on tourism and life for parents and others.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In Scotland, the academic year usually begins in the third week of August.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] In October, there are one or two weeks off, which is the half-way point between Summer and Christmas holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The Christmas holiday usually begins a few days before December 25 and ends a few days after January 5.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is up to a week off half-way through the Spring term and a two-week break for Easter.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] After Easter is Summer term and the 3rd half term break is the half-way point to the summer holidays.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The summer holiday usually begins at the end of June for most pupils in primary 1–7 and secondary years 1–3.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Years 4, 5, and 6 have a period of exam leave at the end of April until early June, but may return for the last few weeks before the summer holiday starts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Schools in Northern Ireland have similar school holidays to those in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Unlike in the rest of the UK or Republic of Ireland, Northern Irish schools operate a 200-day school year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] The school year begins around 1 September, although most schools return up to a week earlier.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is a midterm break in October, in which schools may close for two days to up to a week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] This break falls during the week of Halloween.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Schools close for a week and a half for Christmas, closing around 21 or 22 December, and returning on 3 or 4 January.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] There is another midterm in February, in which most schools close for one week.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] This break is the mid-point between Christmas and Easter.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Schools close for St Patrick's Day on 17 March.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Schools close for Easter on Holy Thursday, and return one week after Easter Monday.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Most schools close for a week at the end of May for the Spring Bank holiday, and return at the start of June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/academic-year-p03] Schools then close for summer on the 30 June.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university is organized around five main campuses situated in Aix-en-Provence and Marseille.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Apart from its major campuses, AMU owns and operates facilities in Arles, Aubagne, Avignon, Digne-les-Bains, Gap, La Ciotat, Lambesc and Salon-de-Provence.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university is headquartered in the 7th arrondissement of Marseille.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] AMU has produced many notable alumni in the fields of law, politics, business, economics, and the arts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] AMU has hundreds of research and teaching partnerships, including close collaboration with the French National Centre for Scientific Research (CNRS), the French Alternative Energies and Atomic Energy Commission (CEA), and *Électricité de France* (EDF).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] AMU is a member of numerous academic organisations including the European University Association (EUA), the Mediterranean Universities Union (UNIMED), and the Udice Group.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The institution developed out of the original University of Provence, founded on 9 December 1409 as a *studium generale* by Louis II of Anjou, Count of Provence, and recognized by papal bull issued by the Pisan Antipope Alexander V.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] However, there is evidence that teaching in Aix existed in some form from the beginning of the 12th century, since there were a doctor of theology in 1100, a doctor of law in 1200 and a professor of law in 1320 on the books.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The decision to establish the university was, in part, a response to the already-thriving University of Paris.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] As a result, in order to be sure of the viability of the new institution, Louis II compelled his *Provençal* students to study in Aix only.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Thus, the letters patent for the university were granted, and the government of the university was created.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Archbishop of Aix-en-Provence, Thomas de Pupio, was appointed as the first chancellor of the university for the rest of his life.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] After his death in 1420, a new chancellor was elected by the rector, masters, and licentiates – an uncommon arrangement not repeated at any other French university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The rector was to be an "ordinary student", who had unrestricted civil and criminal jurisdiction in all cases where one party was a doctor or scholar of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Those displeased with the rector's decisions could appeal to a *doctor legens*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Eleven *consiliarii* provided assistance to the rector, being elected yearly by their predecessors.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] These individuals represented all faculties, but were elected from among the students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The constitution was of a student-university, and the instructors did not have great authority except in granting degrees.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] A resident doctor or student who married was required to pay *charivari* to the university, the amount varying with the degree or status of the man, and being increased if the bride was a widow.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Refusal to submit to this statutable extortion was punished by the assemblage of students at the summons of the rector with frying-pans, bassoons, and horns at the house of the newly married couple.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Continued recusancy was followed by the piling up of dirt in front of their door upon every Feast-day.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] These injunctions were justified on the ground that the money extorted was devoted to divine service.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1481, the County of Provence came under the dominion of the French rule, marking a significant shift in its political landscape.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university's continued existence was approved by Louis XII, and Aix-en-Provence remained a key provincial hub.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It was, for instance, the seat of the Parlement of Aix-en-Provence from 1501 to 1789, no doubt aided by the presence of the law school.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1603, Henry IV established the *Collège Royal de Bourbon* in Aix-en-Provence for the study of *belles-lettres* and philosophy, supplementing the traditional faculties of the university, but not formally a part of it.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] This *college de plain exercice* became a significant seat of learning, under the control of the Jesuits.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, the college frequently served as a preparatory, but unaffiliated, school for the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Only the university was entitled to award degrees in the theology, law, and medicine; but candidates for degrees had first to pass an examination in philosophy, which was only provided by the college.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Universities basically accepted candidates who had studied in colleges formally affiliated with them, which in reality required both college and university to be situated in the same city.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1762 the Jesuits were forced to leave France, and in 1763 the college was officially affiliated with the university as a faculty of arts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The addition of the *Collège Royal de Bourbon* essentially widened the scope of courses provided at the University of Provence.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Formal instruction in French was initially provided at the college, with texts and a structured course of study.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Physics later became a part of the curriculum at the college as a part of the philosophy course in the 18th century.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1741, equipment for conducting experiments was acquired, and the first experimental physics course was offered at Aix-en-Provence.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Classical mechanics, however, was only taught after 1755, when the physicist Aimé-Henri Paulian offered his first class and Isaac Newton's *Principia* and commentaries were obtained for the library.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] , which used to be part of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Subsequently, Cézanne enrolled in the university's law school.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Another point of significance is that much later, in 1852, Paul Cézanne entered the *Collège Royal de Bourbon* where he met and befriended Émile Zola.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] This friendship was decisive for both men so they had successful careers – Cézanne as a painter and Zola as a writer.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Among their closest friends at the college was Baptistin Baille, who went on to become a notable scientist and industrialist; together they were famously known as *les trois inséparables* (the three inseparables).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The French Revolution, with its focus on the individual and an end to inherited privilege, saw the suppression of the universities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] To the revolutionaries, universities embodied bastions of corporatism and established interests.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Moreover, lands owned by the universities and utilized for their support, represented a source of wealth to be tapped by the revolutionary government, just as property possessed by the French Catholic Church had been confiscated.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1792, the University of Provence, along with twenty-one other universities, was dissolved.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Specialized ecoles, with rigorous entrance examinations and open to anyone with talent, were eventually created in order to offer professional training in specialized areas.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Nonetheless, the government found it necessary to allow the faculties of law and medicine to continue in Aix-en-Provence and Marseille in the early 19th century.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The founding of the Imperial University of France in 1806 marked a pivotal moment in the educational landscape at the dawn of the 19th century; it was one of the cornerstones of Napoleon's institutional reconstruction.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Dedicated entirely to cultivating the managerial workforce that the country urgently needed, the Imperial University particularly focused on the fields of law and medicine.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Consequently, in 1804, twelve law schools were reinstated by Napoleon, including that of Aix, which became part of the Imperial University in 1806.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1818, *École de Médecine* was created in Marseille in order to train doctors in colonial medicine for France's expanding colonial empire.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Subsequently, additional faculties were opened in Aix-en-Provence and Marseille to serve the changing needs of French society.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Later, the departmental council of the Bouches-du-Rhône founded a chair in the faculty of letters at Aix-en-Provence in the language and literature of southern Europe; their aim was to assist the commercial exploitation of the region by French business.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1854, a new science faculty was created in Marseille to support the growing industrialization of the region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The most significant development for the university in the 19th century, nevertheless, was the recreation of French universities in 1896.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The various faculties in Aix-en-Provence and Marseille were grouped into the new University of Aix-Marseille.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Through two world wars and an economic depression, the University of Aix-Marseille continued to develop.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Increasing numbers of women and foreign students joined the student body, and an overwhelming majority of students majored in the science, medicine, and law.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Individual faculties were almost autonomous from university administration and the Ministry of Education frequently intervened directly among the faculties.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Following riots among university students in May 1968, a reform of French education occurred.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Orientation Act *(Loi d'Orientation de l'Enseignement Superieur)* of 1968 divided the old faculties into smaller subject departments, decreased the power of the Ministry of Education, and created smaller universities, with strengthened administrations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Subsequently, the University of Aix-Marseille was divided into two institutions.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1973, conservative faculty members led by Charles Debbasch, demanded and obtained the creation of the **University of Aix-Marseille III**, grouping law, political science, applied economics, earth science, ecology and technological studies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Nearly 40 years later, in June 2007, the three universities of Aix-Marseille expressed their intention to reunite in order to form one university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The reunification was gradually prepared, respecting a schedule which allowed for long discussions at each stage, after which it was approved by vote of the Board of Directors of each university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Thus, Aix-Marseille University was re-established by decree No.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] 2011–1010 of 24 August 2011 and officially opened its doors on 1 January 2012.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In addition, the University Institute of Technology and Institute of Teaching and Education are part of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] AMU is governed by the President, the Vice Presidents, the General Director of Services and Deputy Directors General of Services and the Accounting Officer.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] They meet on a weekly basis to discuss the main affairs of the university and to devise the strategic orientations which will be examined by the university councils.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] A second meeting with all the deans and directors takes place immediately afterwards to discuss more specific issues regarding internal activities of the various faculties and schools.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Administrative Council comprises 30 members: academics, teaching staff, administrative and technical personnel, students and external members.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Its role is to determine the university general policy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Academic Council consists of two bodies: The Research Committee, composed of 40 members, drafts policy proposals for research, scientific and technical documentation, and the allocation of research funding.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Education and Student Life Committee, composed of 40 members, drafts policy proposals on the curriculum, on requests for authorization and projects for new programs, and on the assessment of programs and teaching.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] If the President of the university is the most important actor in defining the mission and the strategies of the university, he also has the necessary power to impulse or to sustain the projects that relate to these strategies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Before implementing these projects, they have to be accepted by the university council and if necessary they have to be included in the planning processes.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] There are two main planning processes in the definition of projects in the university that have to be followed in order to be financed or even authorised and accredited by the public (national and local) authorities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The first process takes place every six years and involves the central government, the region as well as the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It is devoted to major investment projects, for instance building a new school, a new campus, a new library, etc.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It is a catalogue of projects and for each of them it defines the financial burden accepted by each partner in the contract.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The second process covers four years and has to be approved by the French Ministry of Education.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In this process, the university sets its objectives at the pedagogical and research levels (new degrees, research projects).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] This planning process is very important because the university is free to define its own strategy, to be approved by the decision makers.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Each process generates an important brainstorming period at all levels of the university in order to identify and build new ideas, new needs, and opportunities, to prioritise them, after an analysis of strengths and weaknesses.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Other choices can be made after each process is closed, but they are more difficult to implement because other sources of funding and other ways of authorisation must be found.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Aix-Marseille University enrolls about 80,000 students, including more than 10,000 international students from 128 different countries.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] With 132 recognized research units and 21 faculties, it particularly concentrates on social and natural sciences.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university engages in the establishment of a European education and research area through over 500 international agreements and promotes mobility development.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] A policy targeted at Asian countries has resulted in an increase in enrolments of excellent international students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Programs in French and/or English have been arranged to enhance the welcome and integration of international students, particularly through the University Service of French as a Foreign Language (SUFLE).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Its predecessor, the Institute of French Studies for Foreign Students *(Institut d'Etudes Françaises Pour Etudiants Etrangers (IEFEE))* was founded in 1953 and was considered one of the premier French-language teaching centers in the country.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] About a thousand students from 65 countries attend the SUFLE throughout the academic year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It also serves as an important center for teachers of French for international learners, aimed at providing education and honing French linguistic capabilities as a tool for scientific and cultural communication.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] According to Harvard University's website, the university is "one of the most distinguished in France, second only to the University of Paris in the areas of French literature, history, and linguistics".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university's library system comprises 59 libraries, with 662,000 volumes, 20,000 online periodical titles, and thousands of digital resources, making it one of the largest and most diverse academic library systems in France.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The overall area occupied by the libraries is equal to 37,056 m2, including 19,703 m2 public access space.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The libraries offer 49.2 kilometers of open-stacks shelving and 4,219 seats for student study.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In addition, there are 487 computer workstations, which are available to the public for research purposes.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university's Institute of Political Studies *(Institut d'études politiques d'Aix-en-Provence)*, also known as *Sciences Po Aix*, was established in 1956.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] *Sciences Po Aix* is a separate and fully independent legal entity within the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It is one of a network of 10 world-famous IEPs *(Instituts d'études politiques)* in France, including those in Bordeaux, Grenoble, Lille, Lyon, Paris, Rennes, Saint-Germain-en-Laye, Strasbourg and Toulouse.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] *Sciences Po Aix* is a *grande école* in political science and its primary aim is to train senior executives for the public, semi-public, and private sectors.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Although the institute offers a multitude of disciplines, its main focus is on politics, including related subjects such as history, law, economics, languages, international relations, and media studies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Its admissions process is among the toughest and most selective in the country.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] *Sciences Po Aix* has numerous exchange programs through partnerships with about 120 different universities in the world: the school therefore welcomes 200 foreign students a year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] On top of these academic exchanges, students have the opportunity to do internships abroad in large international firms.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Many of the institute's graduates have gone on to high positions within both the French government and in foreign governments.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The establishment of the law school at AMU can be traced back to the university's foundation in 1409.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The school had far-reaching influence, since written law, which in France originated in Aix-en-Provence, spread from there, eventually replacing the common law practiced throughout the rest of northern Gaul.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The law school has a long tradition of self-management, with a strongly institutionalized culture and practices enrooted in the social and economic realities of the region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Today, it is one of the largest law schools in France, and is considered to be one of the nation's leading centers for legal research and teaching.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The school is unique among French law schools for the breadth of courses offered and the extent of research undertaken in a wide range of fields.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] For 2024, the law school is ranked 4th in France for its undergraduate studies by THE, QS, and *Le Figaro* rankings, 5th by *Parcoursup*, and 7th by Eduniversal.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] According to the University of Connecticut's website, "other than the Sorbonne, Aix has attracted the most prestigious law faculty in France".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The teaching faculty comprises 155 professors and 172 adjunct lecturers, the latter drawn from private practice, the civil service, the judiciary and other organizations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Much of the legal research at the university is done under the auspices of its many research institutes – there is one in almost every field of law.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Research activity is buttressed by a network of libraries, which holds an impressive collection of monographs and periodicals, including an important collection of 16th-century manuscripts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Moreover, the libraries have several specialized rooms dedicated to specific fields of law, in particular in International and European Law and Legal Theory.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The school has also educated two Nobel laureates: René Cassin, winner of the 1968 Nobel Peace Prize, and Frédéric Mistral, winner of the 1904 Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Alumni also include the 3rd President of Lebanon, Émile Eddé, former Prime Minister of Bulgaria, Vasil Kolarov, former Prime Minister of Angola, Fernando José de França Dias Van-Dúnem, and former Prime Minister of Cambodia, Norodom Ranariddh.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In addition, from 1858 to 1861, a prominent French artist and Post-Impressionist painter Paul Cézanne attended the school, while also receiving drawing lessons.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Aix-Marseille Graduate School of Management, commonly known as IAE Aix-en-Provence, was the first Graduate School of Management in the French public university system.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] According to The Independent, IAE Aix is "a prestigious, double-accredited institution, with an international approach to business combining both classic and innovative teaching methods".
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It is the only French public university entity to receive dual international accreditation: the European standard of excellence EQUIS in 1999, and the AMBA accreditation in 2004 for its MBA Change & Innovation, in 2005 for its master's programs and in 2007 for its Executive Part-time MBA.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The school is composed of 40 permanent faculty members, and invites more than 30 international professors and 150 business speakers each year to conduct lectures and courses within the various programs.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] IAE Aix offers graduate level programs in general management, international management, internal audit of organisations, service management, internal and external communications management, management and information technologies, international financial management and applied marketing.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 2011, the M.Sc. in General Management was ranked 2nd in France along with the M.Sc. in Services Management and Marketing being ranked 3rd and the M.Sc. in Audit and Corporate Governance also being ranked 3rd in the country by *SMBG*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1990, IAE Aix and ESSEC Business School *(École Supérieure des Sciences Economiques et Commerciales)* signed an agreement to unite and offer a joint Doctorate Program, allowing ESSEC professors to teach in the Research Oriented Master program in Aix-en-Provence.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Furthermore, after Research Oriented Master graduation, students can attend the ESSEC Doctorate seminars and have an ESSEC Research Advisor *(Directeur de Recherche)*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the same way, ESSEC students can enroll in the IAE Aix's Research Oriented Master and Doctorate programs.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In both cases, the members of the thesis juries come from both IAE Aix and ESSEC.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Doctorate title is awarded by Aix-Marseille University.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] GREQAM is a research center which specializes in all areas of economics, with strong concentrations in macroeconomics, econometrics, game theory, economic philosophy and public economics.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It counts two Fellows of the Econometric Society among its members, and is consistently ranked as one of the top 5 research centers in economics in France.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] SESSTIM consists of three teams in social and economic sciences, as well as social epidemiology, focusing on applications in the following fields: cancer, infectious and transmissible diseases, and aging.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] IDEP aims at federating competences in the field of Public Economics broadly defined as the part of economics that studies the causes and the consequences of public intervention in the economic sphere.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] AMSE has a triple aim in terms of research development about "Globalization and public action", education regarding Master and PhD degrees and valorization toward local authorities, administrations and corporations, and of information aiming at all public.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The AMSE Master is a two-year Master program in Economics jointly organized with the School for Advanced Studies in the Social Sciences (EHESS) and *Centrale Méditerranée*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It aims to provide high-level courses and training in the main fields of specialization of AMSE: Development Economics, Econometrics, Public Economics, Environmental Economics, Finance/Insurance, Macroeconomics, Economic Philosophy, and Health Economics.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The doctoral program of AMSE brings together more than seventy PhD students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Ten to fifteen new PhD students join the program each year.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] These PhD students cover all the research topics available at AMSE.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The PhD program is a member of the European Doctoral Group in Economics (EDGE) with the University of Cambridge, the University of Copenhagen, University College Dublin, Bocconi University, and LMU Munich.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Faculty of Medicine at AMU can trace its origins to 1413 and became a Faculty of Medical Arts in 1557.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1645, it was transformed into a college of medicine and recognized by a decree issued by the Council of State in 1683.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] During the revolution, although a faculty of medicine was created in Montpellier, Marseille was left aside, probably because of its close proximity.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In 1818, *École de Médecine et de Pharmacie* was founded at *Hôtel-Dieu* and this later became an *École de Plein Exercice*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] This educational establishment experienced remarkable success and continued to expand, enrolling 37 students in the official program and 24 in the doctoral track in 1835.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] By 1893, the student body had grown to 360, with 153 pursuing a degree in medicine.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] As the number of students increased, the facilities became insufficient, leading to the relocation of the school to the *Pavillon Daviel* in 1875, and subsequently to the *Palais du Pharo* in 1893.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] However, it was not until 1930 that a faculty of medicine was formally organised in Marseille.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The town's geographical position meant that it was able to exert a strong influence upon the Mediterranean.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The most significant example of this was Antoine Clot, known as Clot Bey, who with the help of Muhammad Ali of Egypt, founded a school of medicine in Cairo in 1827.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] This enabled Egyptian students to travel to France and encouraged exchanges between western and eastern medicine.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In Marseille, medical practices adapted to tropical diseases developed under the influence of the military department of medicine.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Physiology at the faculty dates back to Charles-Marie Livon, who was named *professeur suppléant* (deputy professor) and then *professeur agrégé* (associate professor) of anatomy and physiology having presented his thesis in Paris.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] He conducted research on hypophysis and pneumogastric physiology, which earned him the Monthyon Prize at the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Following his work with Louis Pasteur, he opened an anti-rabies clinic and became Mayor of Marseille in 1895.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The first dean of the faculty was Leon Imbert, who arrived in Marseille in 1904 as a former *interne des hôpitaux* and *professeur agrégé* at the Montpellier faculty.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Originally a surgeon, he established one of the first centers for maxillofacial prosthetics for the *gueules cassées* (broken faces) of the Great War.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] An anti-cancer center was developed by Lucien Cornill, who was originally from Vichy and studied in Paris.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] During the First World War, he worked at the neurological center in the 7th Military region of Besançon under the supervision of Gustave Roussy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] After the war, he became a *professeur agrégé* of pathological anatomy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] He became dean of the faculty in 1937 and held this position until 1952.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] His main work related to clinical neurology and medullary pathology.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The Faculty of Pharmacy began its independent operations after separating from the main faculty in 1970.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Subsequently, the Faculty of Dentistry also became independent from the Faculty of Medicine, allowing for more specialized programs.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Therefore, these three faculties constitute the Division of Health at the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The university's Astronomy Observatory of Marseille-Provence (OAMP) was established in 1702.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] It is one of the French National Observatories under the auspices of the National Institute of Astronomy (INSU) of the National Centre for Scientific Research (CNRS), with a large financial participation by the National Centre for Space Studies (CNES).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Basic research at the OAMP is organized around three priority themes: cosmology and research on dark matter and dark energy, galaxy formation and evolution, stellar and planetary system formation and exploration of the Solar System.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The OAMP also contributes to the area of environmental sciences and especially the study of the climatic system.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The OAMP is very active in technological research and development, mainly in optics and opto-mechanics, for the development of the main observational instruments that will be deployed on the ground and in space in the coming decades.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] For many years OAMP research teams have had close ties with the French and European space and optical industry.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The OAMP takes part in university education in astrophysics, physics and mathematics, as well as in instrumentation and signal processing from the first year of university to the doctorate level.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] These programs lead to openings in the fields of research and high-tech industry.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The OAMP organizes many astronomy outreach activities in order to share important discoveries with the public.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The OAMP consists of two establishments: the Laboratory of Astrophysics of Marseille (LAM) and the Haute-Provence Observatory (OHP), along with the *Département Gassendi*, which is a common administrative and technical support unit.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] With over 50 researchers, 160 engineers, technical and administrative personnel, plus some 20 graduate students and post-docs, the OAMP is one of the most important research institutes in the region.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Polytech Marseille is a *Grande École d'Ingénieurs* (Graduate School of Science and Engineering), part of AMU.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The School offers 8 specialist courses in emerging technologies which lead to an engineering degree after 5 years of studies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Polytech Marseille is also a member of the Polytech Group which comprises 13 engineering schools of French leading universities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Polytech Marseille's advanced level courses have a strong professional focus.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] They include compulsory work placements in a professional organisation.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] These programs also benefit from a top rank scientific environment, with teaching staff drawn from laboratories attached to major French research organisations that are among the leaders in their field.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] The courses are also accredited by EUR-ACE.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2025 Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU), AMU was ranked joint 151st–200th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2025 Times Higher Education World University Rankings (THE), AMU was ranked joint 401st–500th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the subject tables it was ranked joint 126th–150th in the world for Arts and Humanities, joint 201st–250th in the world for Medical and Health, and joint 251st–300th in the world for Education Studies, Law, Life Sciences, Psychology, and Physical Sciences.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2026 QS World University Rankings (QS), AMU was ranked joint 428th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] News & World Report Best Global Universities Ranking, AMU was ranked joint 226th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2025 CWTS Leiden Ranking, AMU was ranked 226th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2024/25 University Ranking by Academic Performance (URAP), AMU was ranked 143rd in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2025 Center for World University Rankings (CWUR), AMU was ranked 169th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] In the 2019 Reuters - The World's Most Innovative Universities ranking, AMU was ranked 96th in the world.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] AMU has produced many alumni that have distinguished themselves in their respective fields.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/aix-marseille-university-p01] Notable AMU alumni include four Nobel Prize laureates, a two-time recipient of the Pulitzer Prize, six César Award winners, four Olympic medalists and numerous members of the component academies of the *Institut de France*.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The **Autonomous University of Madrid** (Spanish: *Universidad Autónoma de Madrid*; **UAM**), commonly known as **la Autónoma**, is a Spanish public university located in Madrid, Spain.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The university was founded in 1968 by royal decree.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM is widely respected as one of the most prestigious universities in Europe.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] According to the QS World University Rankings 2022, UAM is ranked as the top university in Spain and has consistently ranked as #1 in Spain in the *El País* University rankings, published annually.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Among its notable alumni, which include every president that the Supreme Court of Spain and Constitutional Court of Spain has had, is the current King of Spain, Felipe VI, who studied the Licenciatura en Derecho (Law) and is the president of UAM’s alumni society.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus of the university spans a rural tract of 650 acres (260 ha), mostly around metropolitan Madrid.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Founded in 1968, its main campus, Cantoblanco, is located near the cities of Alcobendas, San Sebastián de los Reyes and Tres Cantos.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's Cantoblanco Campus holds most of the university's facilities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Of these, nearly 770,000 m2 (8,300,000 sq ft) are urbanised and about a third of them are garden areas.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM offers 94 doctorate programs across the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] According to a study carried out by the newspaper *El Mundo*, in 2021, UAM was the best university in the country to study biology, nursing, medicine, physics and law, within the 50 careers with the highest demand.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Stabilization Plan of 1959 and the development plans of the 1960s boosted the Spanish economy after years of austerity and the self-sufficiency-based economy.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The end of diplomatic and economic isolation led to an economic boom in Spain that resulted in the consolidation of a middle class similar to that of other Western European nations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The demand for higher education increased, and the Spanish university system grew increasingly congested.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Autonomous University of Madrid was established by the 5-1968 Decree approved by the Spanish Council of Ministers during the Francoist dictatorship along with the Autonomous University of Barcelona and the University of Bilbao.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] This decree was sponsored by the then-Minister of Science and Education, José Luis Villar Palasí, in order to restructure the Spanish university system.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The name *Universidad Autónoma de Madrid* first appeared in an executive order by the Ministry which was published on 13 August 1968.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] On 8 June 2018 the Autonomous University of Madrid celebrated its 50th anniversary with a series of commemorative events.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's Cantoblanco Campus is home to most of the university's facilities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is located 15 km north of Madrid and has an extension of over 2,200,000 m2.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Of these are nearly 770,000 are urbanised and about a third of them are garden areas.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus was designed as a university town that was to be self-sufficient, but also would be situated away from Madrid in order to keep student activity against the Francoist dictatorship away from the capital.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Initially, the campus held the faculties of philosophy and liberal arts, law, economics, business management, and science, as well as the rectorate, several other service buildings and sports facilities.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The university's other facilities, the faculty of medicine and the teacher training Santa Maria school are in downtown Madrid.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] There are two other teacher training schools in Segovia and in Cuenca.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The original faculties were housed in interconnected buildings with several patios in between them.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Characteristic to each building is a large number of stairs in its corridors, initially designed to prevent students from running in case of police raids.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Currently, this fact has been considered by many university officials as a setback in the integration of handicapped students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The newest facilities were built in a contemporary style, being more accessible and allowing more free movement to students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Sporting facilities include two swimming pools (an indoor one and an outdoor one), two multiple-use pavilions, and outdoor tennis, football, basketball, paddle tennis, rugby, and futsal and beach volleyball courts.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Other services on campus include 16 cafeterias and other eating facilities, medical services, a pharmacy with optic care, a foreign languages pavilion, and a bookstore.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus also houses several research facilities partnered with the Spanish Scientific Research Council (CSIC).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Cantoblanco Campus is accessible by train belonging to Renfe Cercanias Commuter service (station Cantoblanco-Universidad), or by the Madrid Region Commuter Bus service.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The campus is located in the B1 area of the Madrid Transports Consortium.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's faculty of medicine is located north of Madrid near La Paz teaching hospital (that acts as one of the faculty's teaching hospitals, as Puerta de Hierro Majadahonda Hospital, La Princesa Hospital, Niño Jesús Hospital and Fundación Jiménez Díaz do).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Juan Luis Vives Residence Hall was UAM's first residential facility.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is located in the Plaza Castilla area in northern Madrid.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It has 130 residents and holds several cultural activities for the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] La Cristalera residence is located in Miraflores de la Sierra, a village north of Madrid that was acquired by the university in 1989.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is used for conferences and meetings and is the main centre of UAM's summer courses.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The UAM is divided into eight faculties and superior schools that support and coordinate most of the university's academic and administrative activity.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Each faculty is divided into departments that coordinate the teaching and research of the different subjects.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Researchers can organise into research institutes in order to coordinate their activities in a specific research field.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The university totals up to 59 departments and eight research institutes.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In addition to these, the UAM has seven associate schools, which are not completely part of UAM's administrative structure, but issue UAM-recognised titles and are under UAM's academic regulations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM administration is established according to the 2023 Organic Law of the University System (LOSU).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Senior Academic and Administrative Officer of the Autonomous University of Madrid is the rector, who must be, by law, a chair professor serving in the university, elected every four years with a two-term limit by universal graded suffrage.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The current rector is Amaya Mendikoetxea, chair of English Linguistics, who was elected in 2021, becoming the second woman Rector of the University.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Per the university's social board, the rector also designates the manager as part of his team, which oversees the university's economic and administrative activity.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM's collective government bodies are the University Assembly, The Board of Governors, and The Social Board.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The University Assembly is made up of 153 full professors, 84 students, 27 hired, associate, or emeritus professors, 27 members of the non-teaching personnel, 9 research or teaching trainees, the rector, the secretary-general, and the manager.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It is the highest representative body of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It elaborates the university's general guidelines, changes or passes a new university charter, elects twenty members of the Board of Governors, and elects the university Ombudsman.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Board of Governors is the ordinary governmental body of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It controls and passes regulations on most of the university's academic, personnel, and administrative issues.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Social Board is the body responsible for the relations between the university and society.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Its members are designated by trade unions, the municipality of Madrid, employers unions, companies related to the university, the Madrid Assembly and the Board of Governors of the university.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It also oversees the universities financial activities and passes the university budget.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Faculties are headed by a dean, whilst the responsible of the polytechnic school is called head.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They are elected in the same way as the rector and have also a limit of two four-year terms.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They are aided by vice deans or deputy heads.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They are overseen by a faculty or school board.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Departments are led by the head of the department and overseen by the department council.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM offers Spanish undergraduates fully recognized degrees.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] There are the *Diplomatura* and *Ingenierías Técnicas* (technical engineering), which are three-year studies equivalent to an associate degree.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] *Licenciaturas* and *Ingenierías Superiores* are four to five years studies equivalent to a bachelor's degree.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Along with that, UAM offers second level *licenciaturas*, which allow people who have a diplomatura to obtain a *licenciatura* by taking courses.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In other case, they must have at least the first two or three years of a *licenciatura* and combined degree, which are very popular among Spanish students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] They also offer courses in languages other than Spanish.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM offers 94 PhD programs in all of the universities programs.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It also offers 72 master's degrees, and with the implementation of the Bologna Process 16 recognised master's degrees for the academic year of 2006–07.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In addition, the alliance of the four leading Spanish public Universities, two in Madrid (Autónoma University of Madrid and Universidad Carlos III) and two in Barcelona (Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona, Universitat Pompeu Fabra) allows close collaboration between projects and researchers.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The UAM was ranked first amongst Spanish universities by the El Mundo University Supplement (known as "Las 50 Carreras").
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It has also consistently ranked as the #1 law school in Spain for the past 100 years.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] For the subject "Mathematics" the university was ranked within top 51-75 universities in the world (within top 12 in Europe).
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] It was the Spanish university with the most researchers among the most cited according to the Thomson Reuters ranking citation in 2011.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The Autonomous University of Madrid has an active student body, having organised one of Spain's most important events against the dictatorship in 1976 called the Iberian Peoples Festival.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM has over a hundred student societies covering activities ranging from student unionism to theatre and music.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The oldest active association in UAM is the Law Students Association (AED in Spanish), a left-leaning student union established in 1981.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Furthermore, there are new prominent societies in the field of social sciences, such a Debate Society (Sociedad de Debates UAM) and a Model UN society (UAM-I-MUN), both founded and run mainly by law students.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM does not have a formal student government body, as it has been rejected by students in several occasions, and instead students elect different student unions (usually with difference on political issues) to the different university government bodies.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] UAM is also a festive campus, holding several festivals during spring.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] The most important one was the Spring festival held until 1993, but halted due to overcrowding.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] Since then minor festivals have been held by student associations.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] These festivals usually consist of rock concerts by amateur rock bands (many of which have members that are UAM) from midday until dusk.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] According to university regulations, festival profits have to be destined to charities or to the organisation of cultural events.
[src:autonomous-university-of-madrid/autonomous-university-of-madrid] In 2005, due to overcrowding of the festivals that led to several problems, university officials suspended further festivals until a more convenient place for their celebration would be found.
